<article>
    <h1>Se&#xAD;same Prawn &amp; Scal&#xAD;lop Toast, Uni, Caviar ($58 for three)</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201206/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-06"><time>2020-12-06</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>This luxed-up ver­sion of prawn toast feeds per­fectly into Sin­ga­pore­ans’ love of pre­mium seafood, es­pe­cially sea urchin. And with caviar thrown in, it can­not go wrong.</p>
    <p>Scal­lop mousse is spread over a strip of bread, then cov­ered with a piece of spring-roll skin sprin­kled with se­same seeds and toasted.</p>
    <p>A lightly cooked Ar­gen­tinian red prawn is laid out on it, with a small and lus­cious lump of uni and caviar where its head should be.</p>
    <p>It is a well-crafted com­po­si­tion in which nat­u­ral sweet­ness and salin­ity are per­fectly bal­anced.</p>
    <p>The price is rather hefty be­cause each or­der comes with three pieces. This gets rather awk­ward when you are a party of two or four, so I would sug­gest charg­ing by the slice in­stead.</p>

